e Upside project.=C2=A0
It represents an artificial Infinity Mission: a kind of Pascal=E2=80=99s Wa=
ger with house money.=C2=A0
AT&T was regulated as a utility. Profits were effectively capped and had to=
 be justified to regulators. Excess profits would trigger rate reductions. =
One way to reduce profits was to funnel money into R&D, which AT&T did bett=
er than anyone else.=C2=A0
Bell Labs produced the transistor (1947), photovoltaic cells (1954), Unix (=
1969), information theory (1947), cellular technology (1947), continuous wa=
ve lasers (1958), digital imaging sensors (1969), and communications satell=
ites (1962), among other fundamental inventions.=C2=A0
One way to view Bell Labs was as a way to funnel profits that AT&T wasn=E2=
=80=99t allowed to earn in the present into goodwill and defensibility of t=
hose profits over the long term through innovation and technological moats.=
=C2=A0
It was a kind of quasi-governmental organization, with the then-Infinite-se=
eming Upside of monopolizing the country=E2=80=99s long-distance wires, and=
 the Infinite Downside protection against losing that monopoly.=C2=A0
As Tim Wu writes in The Master Switch, =E2=80=9CIn the United States, the h=
igher consumer prices resulting from monopoly amounted, in effect, to a tax=
 on Americans to fund basic research.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That research created positive externalities =E2=80=93 many of which we=E2=
=80=99ve discussed already, from chips, to solar panels, to lasers =E2=80=
=93 and it also protected AT&T.
In 1934, a Bell Labs engineer named Clarence Hickman invented magnetic tape=
 to be used in answering machines. That invention wouldn=E2=80=99t be disco=
vered until 1994. =E2=80=9CAT&T ordered the Labs to cease all research into=
 magnetic storage, and Hickman=E2=80=99s research was suppressed and concea=
led for more than sixty years,=E2=80=9D Wu writes, because =E2=80=9CAT&T fi=
rmly believed that the answering machine, and its magnetic tapes, would lea=
d the public to abandon the telephone.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That is the crack, the flaw in this third approach, =E2=80=9Cthe essential =
weakness of a centralized approach to innovation,=E2=80=9D as Wu explains i=
t:
Yes, Bell Labs was great. But AT&T, as an innovator, bore a serious genetic=
 flaw: it could not originate technologies that might, by the remotest poss=
ibility, threaten the Bell System. In the language of innovation theory, th=
e output of the Bell Labs was practically restricted to sustaining innovati=
ons; disruptive technologies, those that might even cast a shadow of uncert=
ainty over the business model, were simply out of the question.
Along with the answering machine, Bell Labs =E2=80=9Cwould for years suppre=
ss or fail to market: fiber optics, mobile telephones, digital subscriber l=
ines (DSL), fax machines, speakerphones - the list goes on and on.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
We bemoan the inability to launch modern Manhattan Projects and create mode=
rn Bell Labs, but contrast this with Larry Page=E2=80=99s willingness to go=
 bankrupt to achieve AGI. Perhaps regulated monopoly status prevented both =
the downsides and the upsides from reaching infinity, which threw the wager=
 out of whack.=C2=A0
We may not see more Manhattan Projects or Bell Labs in forms that look like=
 the Manhattan Project or Bell Labs, and that=E2=80=99s OK. Privately-funde=
d Infinity Missions chasing infinite upside may be their new form.
Back to Infinity
Privately funded infinity missions are not without their drawbacks, either.=
=C2=A0
If you believe the AGI x-risk crowd, the infinite profit motive is driving =
these companies to push humanity to the brink whether we like it or not. Pr=
ivate companies don=E2=80=99t have the checks that government-regulated mon=
opolies or government-funded projects do.=C2=A0
That said, as Tyler Cowen points out [ https://substack.com/redirect/6b5e1a=
e3-a62a-4116-aa8d-56105ba6c22e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the Effective Altruist camp is not putting its mo=
ney where its mouth is by shorting the market, and the market overall does =
not seem to price in a high probability that the world is about to end.=C2=
=A0
Whatever your belief, I expect that we will see companies funding Infinity =
Missions more frequently than governments going forward.=C2=A0
Personally, I think that=E2=80=99s a good thing, as it represents a shift f=
rom governments needing to protect against civilization-level threats to co=
mpanies racing to capture civilization-level opportunities.=C2=A0
Why? There are a few reasons.=C2=A0
Technology is exponential [ https://substack.com/redirect/994548a6-387b-4c8=
8-85b2-a7e0eac9f73f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], and we=E2=80=99ve reached a point in our and its evolution a=
t which there are simply more infinite upside opportunities.=C2=A0
Capital markets are better at appreciating and pricing potential infinite u=
pside than governments are. Governments are best-suited for downside protec=
tion; private markets for maximizing upside. And even when the capital mark=
ets are wrong =E2=80=93 as they were in the internet bubble and may certain=
ly be in the race to AGI =E2=80=93 humanity tends to benefit from their ove=
rinvestment.=C2=A0
Funded by those capital markets, private companies now have the resources r=
ivaling governments. It=E2=80=99s not the first time that=E2=80=99s happene=
d =E2=80=93 describing Cornelius Vanderbilt in The First Tycoon [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/d7c7491f-f44c-4651-b58d-d0b07f866a45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], T.J. Stiles wrote, =E2=
=80=9CIf he had been able to sell all his assets at full market value at th=
e moment of his death, in January of that year, he would have taken one out=
 of every twenty dollars in circulation, including cash and demand deposits=
=2E=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 but it is happening at=
 unprecedented scale, and distri=
buted amongst enough companies that they are forced to compete those fortun=
es against each other.=C2=A0
Plus, more of our brightest minds are going into industry than into researc=
h or government, a phenomenon I applauded in OpenAI & Grand Strategy [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/d4b15259-393e-4412-b0da-77bd637c6199?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CCount me=
 among those who would rather our best people start companies to achieve go=
als no old-time general could have dreamed of than kill each other by the h=
undreds of thousands in pursuit of lesser ones.=E2=80=9D War is still terri=
ble, but it is no longer the best way to win glory.=C2=A0
Upside achievement is more appealing than downside protection. If you =E2=
=80=9Cwin=E2=80=9D a nuclear war, everyone, probably you included, dies [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/12b04b6a-56f3-4487-be16-44aafce7ebc0?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. If you achieve=
 AGI, you get unfathomably rich and probably usher humanity into a new gold=
en era.=C2=A0
Finally, it is more possible than ever to reach towards (although never act=
ually to) infinity: to scale globally, and beyond.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ve just touched on one Infinite Upside Infinity Mission =E2=80=
=93 AGI =E2=80=93 but space may be another.=C2=A0
SpaceX is currently in the enviable position of controlling access beyond t=
he earth, and is in the pole position to make humans multiplanetary. That k=
ind of Infinity Mission has attracted some of the world=E2=80=99s most tale=
nted people to happily work unthinkable hours in its pursuit. It is both In=
finite Downside protection in the case of emergency on Earth and Infinite U=
pside opportunity as the economy expands to include more of the universe.=
=C2=A0
There will be more: longevity seems a particularly infinite pursuit. How mu=
ch would you pay to avoid Pascal=E2=80=99s Wager altogether?=C2=A0
All three of these cases =E2=80=93 AGI, Space, and Longevity =E2=80=93 repr=
esent a version of Pascal=E2=80=99s Wager more true to the original bet. Th=
ey both promise infinite upside and threaten infinite downside.=C2=A0
Achieving AGI might usher in utopia, and some argue that if we let China ge=
t there first, we face infinite downside.=C2=A0
Extending Earth=E2=80=99s economy throughout the universe offers infinite u=
pside, and failing to make ourselves multiplanetary =E2=80=93 subjecting ou=
rselves to the risk of putting all of our eggs in one planetary basket =E2=
=80=93 exposes us to infinite downside.=C2=A0
Longevity offers the hope of living forever. Failing to do so leaves us doo=
med to be dead for all eternity, the thing that so freaked me out about inf=
inity as a little kid.=C2=A0
The promise and threat of infinity will drive investments that don=E2=80=99=
t make sense in a finite expected value calculation, but that will accelera=
te progress towards those goals in the process. It=E2=80=99s capitalism wit=
h an irrational turbobooster.=C2=A0
If nothing else, the infinity framing is a useful way to understand why the=
 government can be so good at some things and so bad at others.=C2=A0
We pulled off Operation Warpspeed in part because, at the time, COVID seeme=
d like an existential threat. We can=E2=80=99t seem to get our healthcare s=
ystem in order because it=E2=80=99s more frog-in-boiling-pot.=C2=A0
It also shows where companies can do what people expect governments to. We=
=E2=80=99ve talked about the $42 billion government-funded rural internet p=
roduct that has produced very little rural internet. SpaceX, on the other h=
and, is able to provide rural internet =E2=80=93 most recently for disaster=
 relief after the Hurricanes in North Carolina =E2=80=93 because it=E2=80=
=99s an orthogonal way to fund the company=E2=80=99s Infinity Mission.=C2=
=A0
If the government feels like it=E2=80=99s stagnating, like it couldn=E2=80=
=99t possibly pull off another Manhattan Project, that=E2=80=99s OK. It=E2=
=80=99s almost to be expected. We look to the government for protection, no=
t transcendence.=C2=A0
It even makes sense. Politicians will be long out of office by the time any=
 Infinity Mission they fund comes close to fruition. Their incentive is to =
produce short-term, finite upside while protecting against infinite downsid=
e.=C2=A0
Fortunately, infinity applied to future profits is financially overwhelming=
 enough that companies are incentivized to pursue Infinity Missions, no mat=
ter how small their probability of success or how much it costs today. Now =
that infinity is on the table, I expect it will pull progress further and f=
aster than we=E2=80=99ve seen in the past.=C2=A0
Avoiding Hell is necessary, but not sufficient. The real point of the Wager=
 is to reach Heaven.
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose.=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy

