The Bell Labs Carveout</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We can&#8217;t talk a=
bout big projects that have pushed or pulled technology forward without tal=
king about Bell Labs, so a brief aside.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Founded =
in 1925 inside of AT&amp;T&#8217;s telephone monopoly with the express purp=
ose of improving telephony, it sits somewhere in between a government-funde=
d Infinite Downside protection project and a privately-funded Infinite Upsi=
de project.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>It represents an artificial In=
finity Mission: a kind of </span><strong>Pascal&#8217;s Wager with house mo=
ney</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">AT&amp;T was regulate=
d as a utility. Profits were effectively capped and had to be justified to =
regulators. Excess profits would trigger rate reductions. One way to reduce=
 profits was to funnel money into R&amp;D, which AT&amp;T did better than a=
nyone else.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Bell Labs produced the transistor (1=
947), photovoltaic cells (1954), Unix (1969), information theory (1947), ce=
llular technology (1947), continuous wave lasers (1958), digital imaging se=
nsors (1969), and communications satellites (1962), among other fundamental=
 inventions.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>One way to view Bell Labs w=
as as a way to funnel profits that AT&amp;T wasn&#8217;t allowed to earn in=
 the present into goodwill and defensibility of those profits over the long=
 term through innovation and technological moats.&#160;</strong></p><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">It was a kind of quasi-governmental organization, with the then-=
Infinite-seeming Upside of monopolizing the country&#8217;s long-distance w=
ires, and the Infinite Downside protection against losing that monopoly.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As Tim Wu writes in </span><em>The Master Sw=
itch, </em><span>&#8220;In the United States, the higher consumer prices re=
sulting from monopoly amounted, in effect, to a tax on Americans to fund ba=
sic research.&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That research create=
d positive externalities &#8211; many of which we&#8217;ve discussed alread=
y, from chips, to solar panels, to lasers &#8211; and it also protected AT&=
amp;T.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In 1934, a Bell Labs engineer named Clarence Hi=
ckman invented magnetic tape to be used in answering machines. That inventi=
on wouldn&#8217;t be discovered until 1994. &#8220;AT&amp;T ordered the Lab=
s to cease all research into magnetic storage, and Hickman&#8217;s research=
 was suppressed and concealed for more than sixty years,&#8221; Wu writes, =
because &#8220;AT&amp;T firmly believed that the answering machine, and its=
 magnetic tapes, would lead the public to abandon the telephone.&#8221;&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That is the crack, the flaw in this third approach,=
 &#8220;the essential weakness of a centralized approach to innovation,&#82=
21; as Wu explains it:</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c24=
27; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><=
span>Yes, Bell Labs was great. But AT&amp;T, as an innovator, bore a seriou=
s genetic flaw: it could not originate technologies that might, by the remo=
test possibility, threaten the Bell System. In the language of innovation t=
heory, the output of the Bell Labs was practically restricted to </span><st=
rong>sustaining innovations; </strong><span>disruptive technologies, those =
that might even cast a shadow of uncertainty over the business model, were =
simply out of the question.</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A=
long with the answering machine, Bell Labs &#8220;would for years suppress =
or fail to market: fiber optics, mobile telephones, digital subscriber line=
s (DSL), fax machines, speakerphones - the list goes on and on.&#8221;&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>We bemoan the inability to launch modern Manha=
ttan Projects and create modern Bell Labs, but contrast this with Larry Pag=
e&#8217;s </span><strong>willingness to go bankrupt</strong><span> to achie=
ve AGI. Perhaps regulated monopoly status prevented both the downsides and =
the upsides from reaching infinity, which threw the wager out of whack.&#16=
0;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We may not see more Manhattan Projects or Be=
ll Labs in forms that look like the Manhattan Project or Bell Labs, and tha=
t&#8217;s OK. Privately-funded Infinity Missions chasing infinite upside ma=
y be their new form.</p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" style=3D"--highlig=
ht-bg: rgba(var(--color-bg-accent-themed-rgb), 0.2); -moz-appearance: optim=
izelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: op=
timizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimize=
legibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-family: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-s=
ystem-headline, system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', R=
oboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji',=
 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.1=
6em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Back to Infinity=
</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Privately funded infinity missions are not =
without their drawbacks, either.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If you believe =
the AGI x-risk crowd, the infinite profit motive is driving these companies=
 to push humanity to the brink whether we like it or not. Private companies=
 don&#8217;t have the checks that government-regulated monopolies or govern=
ment-funded projects do.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That said, as Tyl=
er Cowen </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6b5e1ae3-a62a-4116=
-aa8d-56105ba6c22e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline=
;">points out</a><span>, the Effective Altruist camp is not putting its mon=
ey where its mouth is by shorting the market, and the market overall does n=
ot seem to price in a high probability that the world is about to end.&#160=
;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Whatever your belief, </span><strong>I =
expect that we will see companies funding Infinity Missions more frequently=
 than governments going forward.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
Personally, I think that&#8217;s a good thing, as it represents </span><str=
ong>a shift from governments needing to protect against civilization-level =
threats to companies racing to capture civilization-level opportunities</st=
rong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Why? There are a few reasons=
=2E&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=20=
55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Technology is </span><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/994548a6-387b-4c88-85b2-a7e0eac9f73f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">exponential</a><span>, and we&#8=
217;ve reached a point in our and its evolution at which there are simply m=
ore infinite upside opportunities.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Capita=
l markets are better at appreciating and pricing potential infinite upside =
than governments are. Governments are best-suited for downside protection; =
private markets for maximizing upside. And even when the capital markets ar=
e wrong &#8211; as they were in the internet bubble and may certainly be in=
 the race to AGI &#8211; humanity tends to benefit from their overinvestmen=
t.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Funded by those capital markets, privat=
e companies now have the resources rivaling governments. It&#8217;s not the=
 first time that&#8217;s happened &#8211; describing Cornelius Vanderbilt i=
n </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d7c7491f-f44c-4651-b5=
8d-d0b07f866a45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">=
The First Tycoon</a></em><span>, T.J. Stiles wrote, &#8220;If he had been a=
ble to sell all his assets at full market value at the moment of his death,=
 in January of that year, he would have taken one out of every twenty dolla=
rs in circulation, including cash and demand deposits.&#8221; &#8211; but i=
t is happening at unprecedented scale, and distributed amongst enough compa=
nies that they are forced to compete those fortunes against each other.&#16=
0;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Plus, more of our brightest minds are =
going into industry than into research or government, a phenomenon I applau=
ded in </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d4b15259-393e-44=
12-b0da-77bd637c6199?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underli=
ne;">OpenAI &amp; Grand Strategy</a></em><span>: &#8220;Count me among thos=
e who would rather our best people start companies to achieve goals no old-=
time general could have dreamed of than kill each other by the hundreds of =
thousands in pursuit of lesser ones.&#8221; War is still terrible, but it i=
s no longer the best way to win glory.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><s=
pan>Upside achievement is more appealing than downside protection. If you &=
#8220;win&#8221; a nuclear war, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redi=
rect/12b04b6a-56f3-4487-be16-44aafce7ebc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); tex=
t-decoration: underline;">everyone, probably you included, dies</a><span>. =
If you achieve AGI, you get unfathomably rich and probably usher humanity i=
nto a new golden era.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Finally, it is more=
 possible than ever to reach towards (although never actually to) infinity:=
 to scale globally, and beyond.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We&#8217;ve just=
 touched on one Infinite Upside Infinity Mission &#8211; AGI &#8211; but sp=
ace may be another.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">SpaceX is currently in the e=
nviable position of controlling access beyond the earth, and is in the pole=
 position to make humans multiplanetary. That kind of Infinity Mission has =
attracted some of the world&#8217;s most talented people to happily work un=
thinkable hours in its pursuit. It is both Infinite Downside protection in =
the case of emergency on Earth and Infinite Upside opportunity as the econo=
my expands to include more of the universe.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Ther=
e will be more: longevity seems a particularly infinite pursuit. How much w=
ould you pay to avoid Pascal&#8217;s Wager altogether?&#160;</p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">All three of these cases &#8211; AGI, Space, and Longevity &#8211; r=
epresent a version of Pascal&#8217;s Wager more true to the original bet. T=
hey both promise infinite upside and threaten infinite downside.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;">Achieving AGI might usher in utopia, and some argue that i=
f we let China get there first, we face infinite downside.&#160;</p><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">Extending Earth&#8217;s economy throughout the universe offers i=
nfinite upside, and failing to make ourselves multiplanetary &#8211; subjec=
ting ourselves to the risk of putting all of our eggs in one planetary bask=
et &#8211; exposes us to infinite downside.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Long=
evity offers the hope of living forever. Failing to do so leaves us doomed =
to be dead for all eternity, the thing that so freaked me out about infinit=
y as a little kid.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The promise and threat of inf=
inity will drive investments that don&#8217;t make sense in a finite expect=
ed value calculation, but that will accelerate progress towards those goals=
 in the process. It&#8217;s capitalism with an irrational turbobooster.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If nothing else, the infinity framing is a useful w=
ay to understand why the government can be so good at some things and so ba=
d at others.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We pulled off Operation Warpspeed i=
n part because, at the time, COVID seemed like an existential threat. We ca=
n&#8217;t seem to get our healthcare system in order because it&#8217;s mor=
e frog-in-boiling-pot.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It also shows where compa=
nies can do what people expect governments to. We&#8217;ve talked about the=
 $42 billion government-funded rural internet product that has produced ver=
y little rural internet. SpaceX, on the other hand, is able to provide rura=
l internet &#8211; most recently for disaster relief after the Hurricanes i=
n North Carolina &#8211; because it&#8217;s an orthogonal way to fund the c=
ompany&#8217;s Infinity Mission.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If the governme=
nt feels like it&#8217;s stagnating, like it couldn&#8217;t possibly pull o=
ff another Manhattan Project, that&#8217;s OK. It&#8217;s almost to be expe=
cted. We look to the government for protection, not transcendence.&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">It even makes sense. Politicians will be long out of off=
ice by the time any Infinity Mission they fund comes close to fruition. The=
ir incentive is to produce short-term, finite upside while protecting again=
st infinite downside.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Fortunately, infinit=
y applied to future profits is financially overwhelming enough that compani=
es </span><em>are </em><span>incentivized to pursue Infinity Missions, no m=
atter how small their probability of success or how much it costs today. No=
w that infinity is on the table, I expect it will pull progress further and=
 faster than we&#8217;ve seen in the past.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">Avoiding Hell is necessary, but not sufficient. The real point of the Wag=
er is to reach Heaven.</p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
"><hr style=3D"background: #e6e6e6; border: none; height: 1px; margin: 32px=
 0; padding: 0;"></div><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s all for today. We&#82=
17;ll be back in your inbox on Friday with a Weekly Dose. </p><p style=3D"c=
